Reasoning: The paper deals with the performance evaluation of mobile ad-hoc networks (MANETs) using the Aloha medium access scheme, which falls under the category of networked systems (cs.NI). The paper also uses stochastic analysis and information theory concepts to evaluate the end-to-end performance, which suggests the possibility of it belonging to the sub-category of information theory (cs.IT). The paper also discusses the use of fixed relaying nodes, which could fall under the sub-category of multi-agent systems (cs.MA). The paper also discusses the use of Poisson-line MANET models, which could fall under the sub-category of pattern formation and recognition (cs.PF). Finally, the paper discusses the tuning of parameters, which could fall under the sub-category of control systems (cs.SY).
